text: Oh, me first. Yay. Cool. Well, what a month. I mean, a huge month. We had – Well, you're important, Rob. I know I joke about that, but no, another time. So there's – what a huge month. ITSMF New Zealand Conference, right? That's since the last time we spoke, isn't it? I'm struggling to keep up. Yep. Yes, it is. So that was massive. We could have a whole conversation on that in its own right. But as always, went swimmingly, as always. Fantastic little conference. All went very well. Breed had a good time, I think. Karen, over here? I believe so. I've seen some photos. Yeah, lots of good sessions. Good conference. Usual story. They just pull it off every year. It's fantastic. And, of course, the other huge news for the month is the joint venture, Capita and UK government joint venture, where ITIL and Prince2 and the whole Swirl portfolio has been sold to private enterprise on a profit-sharing basis. So, you know, that's the really big news of the month. And then sort of overshadowing, there was the Knowledge13 conference as well. So, you know, quite a bit going on this month. It's been a big one. Absolutely. So, Simone, what about you? Busy, busy, busy, I think, like most people. I was until my Foursquare account announced that I've been at airports each week for over a month. Between training and projects and all the admin has definitely fallen by the wayside. I think the office is going to get a bit of a shock when it finally gets the reimbursement spreadsheet. It has been, I think, it's going to be very busy in the coming months too for me, just finding out some stuff going on. Being chosen for TFT13. Woo-hoo! So, that was brilliant. So, I'm really excited to have that opportunity again. Also got an interesting ITSMFA New South Wales seminar coming up. I'm presenting alongside Kim Sealing-Smith, who was a keynote, of course, last year, and her people stuff. And I'm talking about a novel way of leading. Also facilitating at KM Australia's conference in July, doing a workshop on knowledge-centred support. So, that's also exciting. I've been laughing at myself uproariously when I realised that a personal project I had going on, that I started using the ITSM frameworks to help get me through all the timeframes. The joint venture, yes, that Rob mentioned, the Capita, I just read a really nice article on that. It was in the Best Management Practice e-bulletin, the first issue. So, I'll give the link to that. I just really hope, it does answer some questions, but I just really hope that it comes out in reality of what they're saying. And Rob, I noticed that you had on the Skeptic site a little blog about the Bulletin Castle. So, hoping that people can have their little rant there and see what comes out of it all. Yeah, the JV has Chris Bartlett as a guy working for the joint venture, who's been doing massive work around the old hearts and minds, reaching out and popping up on our sister podcast in the US. They interviewed him and ITSM Review magazine has had a couple of good articles on the JV, including a conversation with Chris again. So, they certainly are coming outside the castle and walking around amongst the peasants and pressing the flesh. So, they're opening up lines of communication far more than Castle Eitel ever did in the past. So, yeah, we live in hope that that will actually come to mean something substantial over time. Yeah. It's actually interesting. Just very recently on Facebook, back to ITSM, Ale Rus actually put up a question about how do people know the Eitel is a great body of knowledge? So, there's great discussions going on there as well. So, I think it is generating a lot of curiosity. Absolutely. And Rob and I have been talking about a future subject, and I've copied you guys as well, that we might talk about what's the impact going to be? Does people even care in terms of the Eitel or IT service management community? So, we'll have that discussion. But yes, interesting times. And I heard just today, someone told me that Capitra just bought some call centre somewhere as well. So, they've got some call centre, Eitel and Swirl, and G2G3, of course. So, let's put the jigsaw together and see what it looks like. A couple of months in review has been bum up, head down in Canberra. And it's going to continue like that for the next month. So, yeah, nothing much to add apart from, as Rob said, the New Zealand conference, which I followed the Twitters and the Facebook things, and that was really interesting. And it sounds like it went really well. And yeah, the joint venture. So, let's see what happens. So, this week's topic, which I know we're all very passionate about, is customer satisfaction. And we have a special guest with us, Dave O'Riordan. And I'll just introduce Dave. Dave's Managing Director of SilverSix, an Australian management consultancy that helps IT departments measure and improve internal customer satisfaction with IT. Dave has worked in IT for 20 years. Doesn't look that old. There you go. Working for blue chip organisations such as IBM, Accenture, in the UK, Europe, and Asia Pacific. Dave has spent most of the last decade consulting to IT teams who want to measurably improve customer satisfaction with IT. Dave is known for his passion. I've grabbed this off his website. Great. Dave is known for his passion for bridging the gap between IT and the business. So, welcome, Dave. How are you? Good. Thank you, Karen. Thank you for that introduction. And hi, Simone and Rob. So, Dave, knowing that your passion's all about, and I know you do other stuff, but it's about customer satisfaction. And we all know that, you know, customer sat is crucial for service improvement if IT departments are committed to doing that. So, one of the first things I wanted to ask you is, you know, what are some of the mistakes that most organisations or most people make when they try to glean what their internal customer satisfaction is? Well, probably the first, the biggest mistake is probably not trying to glean it at all. Which we're going to talk about is surveying your customers, your internal customers. But based on a very unscientific method, which is just straw poll votes that I present on this topic, you know, we're typically finding that something like 20% of IT departments are not surveying or measuring customer satisfaction at all. And roughly another 20% are doing it so infrequently as to not really be very valuable. So, my number one would be not trying to glean it. Is that because they don't want to know? That's a good, that's a great question. I think more commonly, Karen, we come across is that they think they know because they're relying on who shouts loudest. And we do come across don't want to know, but I think more commonly it's why would I want to actually measure this or attempt to get anything objective back? I've got my finger on the pulse. I don't need to actually do any more than that. And also, Dave, there's the distinction between customer satisfaction and user satisfaction too, isn't there? So, if you're an in-house IT department with a very small number of customers who are effectively peers of the CIO, you know, you get that mentality in IT too where they think, you know, we know what the customers, like the four customers think. So, therefore, we understand the situation without really knowing anything at all about what the actual users think. And I'm probably at risk of confusing the listeners. When I talk about customers, I tend to use that inclusively to mean, you know, economic buyers as well as users. Yeah. I wonder, Dave, if it's not just about, you know, it is quite common to shout loudest thing because I know that there's a lot of resource issues and I think, well, there's all this extra effort and time to actually sit down and ask these questions and so on. But do you think they still see themselves as that utility, you know, as opposed to actually being partnering and being part of the organisation? Yeah, I think that's probably part of it, Simone. Although increasingly due to, you know, conferences, the ITSM conferences, I think people are beginning, the whole term service management implies that we're doing more than providing utility. So, I think that people are swinging around to not feeling like it's all about technology. I notice you've got a degree in psychology, Dave. So, you're obviously tapped into, you know, all three of us in our own way on this podcast are quite passionate about the people side of things and you're obviously tapped into that too. You don't sound like the kind of guy who falls into the technology trap either. No, the funny thing is that when I was choosing my degree, I wanted to do IT because I felt that was where the money was and I enjoyed it and psychology because I thought that would be more interesting and it has sort of proven to be the case. So, yes, I really enjoy the people side of things and I've had a few scary experiences at parties as most of us have when someone asks what you do and you say you work in IT and then all of a sudden the person you're talking to has turned their back to go and find someone else more interesting to talk to. And I think I've been scarred from that and so I'm in my own way trying to set out and change IT's reputation to be more, you know, people focused. Start off with the psychology of IT. I was going to say, when they ask you, say I'm a psychologist. I'm an IT psychologist. I would love to be able to claim that I'm an expert clinical psychologist but I think in a four-year course you pretty much learn what the different subject areas are and become a specialist in none of them. But I don't tell people that. I'm happy for them to believe I'm an expert in all fields of psychology.
